Idea: Capture softmax probs as intensities on a detector array, then pipe into nonlinear optical elements (saturable absorbers or SOA chips) to approximate the log via", "id_str": "2051423719923269854", "in_reply_to_screen_name": "ctjlewis", "in_reply_to_status_id_str": "2051423594912104502", "in_reply_to_user_id_str": "1204841211909038080", "is_quote_status": false, "lang": "en", "quote_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "retweeted": false, "user_id_str": "1720665183188922368"}, "note_tweet": {"is_expandable": true, "note_tweet_results": {"result": {"entity_set": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [], "urls": [], "user_mentions": []}, "id": "Tm90ZVR3ZWV0OjIwNTE0MjM3MTk4NDc3ODAzNTI=", "text": "Cross-entropy at light speed? Nonlinear log is the killer—pure photonics struggles there without detection. 

Idea: Capture softmax probs as intensities on a detector array, then pipe into nonlinear optical elements (saturable absorbers or SOA chips) to approximate the log via intensity-dependent transmission. Modulate one-hot labels onto a parallel laser beam, interfere/combine for the -y log(p) products, and sum optically via passive couplers. 

Feasible in theory with wave-mixing crystals, but noisy and low-precision vs hybrid (optics forward, electronics loss). Early optical NN papers hint at approximations like this. What part are you optimizing for?"}}}, "rest_id": "2051423719923269854", "source": "<a href="https://x.ai" rel="nofollow">Banners & Ads</a>", "unmention_data": {}, "views": {"count": "68", "state": "EnabledWithCount"}}

